Licence:    Apache License, Version 2.0 (see LICENSE-cisco-apache-2.0)

The rule corpus (YAML signatures, YARA rules, scan policies, LLM-judge prompt
templates, and the rule-pack `__init__.py` files) is vendored unchanged from
the cisco-ai-defense/skill-scanner project at the SHA noted above. Files are
preserved with their original content; the rule engine that loads them is a
separate, Charon-native implementation.

Modifications to these vendored files, if any are made, will be marked with
a "Modified by Charon" comment at the top of the file per Apache-2.0 §4(b).

Per Apache-2.0 §4, a copy of the licence is included at LICENSE-cisco-apache-2.0.
No NOTICE file was present in the upstream repo at the vendored SHA, so this
attribution is the canonical record of the borrow.

### ui-ux-pro-max-skill — design-knowledge dataset

Location:   07-References/design-system-data/
Source:     https://github.com/nextlevelbuilder/ui-ux-pro-max-skill  (v2.6.2)
Copyright:  © 2024 Next Level Builder
Licence:    MIT (see 07-References/design-system-data/LICENSE-ui-ux-pro-max)

The CSV tables under 07-References/design-system-data/ (UX guidelines, chart
selection, UI styles, colour palettes, typography pairings, motion tiers,
landing patterns, product archetypes, icons, app-interface rules) are the data
files from the ui-ux-pro-max-skill project, adapted for use as a harness-native
markdown reference (07-References/design-system-reference.md). Only the data was
borrowed — the upstream npm CLI and Python BM25 search machinery were not, and
no upstream code was executed during extraction. The upstream's Google-Fonts
catalogue, native-app-stack tables, and Chinese-language design.csv were
excluded as out-of-scope for web-surface work. Per the MIT licence, the
copyright and permission notice are preserved at the path noted above.
